China's investment relies on
<s>BEIJING — China's economy unexpectedly slowed in the second quarter this year.
<s>What is also unexpected is that most of the data released since July suggests that growth has stabilized.
<s>No wonder the market let out a collective sigh of relief.
<s>Should investors remain on edge?
Currently, the most serious problem facing the Chinese authorities is overcapacity.
For instance, China's crude steel annual capacity is ten billion tons, but the total production in 2012 was only 720 million tons – or a utilization rate of 72%.
More strikingly, the steel industry's profit margin in 2012 was only 0.04%.
In fact, the profit per ton of steel produced can buy only a lollipop.
So far this year, the average profit margin for China's top 500 companies is 4.34%, down 33 basis points from 2012.
Some say that today's overcapacity stems from excessive investment in the past.
Others argue that overcapacity is due to insufficient effective demand.
The government's view seems to be a compromise between the two.
On one hand, authorities are asking thousands of companies to cut back on production capacity.
On the other hand, the government has introduced some "mini-stimulus" measures, such as exempting micro-enterprises from business tax and value-added tax, and requiring banks to increase loans to export-oriented enterprises.
#1 <s>The official government narrative is that China's growth model needs to reduce investment and increase consumption.
#2 <s>But not all Chinese economists agree with this view.
#3 <s>They argue that capital stock is a key factor in growth, and since China's per capita capital stock is still relatively low compared to developed countries, there is significant potential for future investment.
#4 <s>Indeed, capital accumulation has been a major driver of economic growth, and catching up to developed countries' income levels requires China to continue increasing its capital stock over the long term.
#5 <s>But what matters is not the scale of the capital stock or even the level of investment; what matters is the rate of investment growth, which has been much higher than GDP growth rates for decades.
According to official statistics, China's investment rate has approached 50% of GDP.
Benefiting from absorption constraints, capital efficiency declines steadily as the scale of capital increases.
Factoring in the environmental destruction caused by the rapid growth in investment, China's capital efficiency would be even lower.
The role of human capital and technological progress in economic growth is no less significant than that of physical capital and labor.
If resources are allocated towards physical capital at the expense of undermining the accumulation of human capital – which is a prerequisite for full consumption – economic growth is more likely to slow down rather than accelerate.
Therefore, China should lower its investment growth rate and raise its consumption growth rate, stabilizing the investment ratio at a more sustainable level.
Naturally, it is not entirely wrong to say that China's overcapacity reflects a lack of effective demand.
But where does effective demand come from?
In this regard, the steel industry in China once again provides a good example.
Despite having no comparative advantage in steel production, China built approximately one thousand steel plants, accounting for half of the global production.
As early as 2004, the Chinese government tried to cool down overinvestment; but due to strong demand from infrastructure investment and real estate development, output continued to grow rapidly, increasing from 300 million tons that year to 1 billion tons in 2012.
China's investments can be roughly divided into three categories: manufacturing, infrastructure, and real estate.
At the peak of the global financial crisis at the end of 2008 and in 2009, infrastructure investment stimulated by economic stimulus packages maintained growth in output.
In 2010, real estate development investment became the main driver of growth, replacing infrastructure investment.
Today, both infrastructure and real estate are major drivers of China's growth.
China indeed needs more infrastructure investment — particularly in power and hydroelectric, transportation, and communications.
But the investment pace must take financial constraints into full consideration.
More importantly, China can and should invest more in social infrastructure such as schools, hospitals, and nursing homes.
But real estate investment is a different matter.
It's difficult to assess the severity of China's property bubble and when it might burst.
But one thing is certain: China has already invested too much in real estate development.
China's per capita income is less than $6,000, but the home ownership rate in China is as high as around 90%, while it is less than 70% in the United States.
The per capita housing area is 32.9 square meters, while the median family housing area in Hong Kong just reaches 48 square meters.
There are 696 five-star hotels in China, with another 500 under construction.
Out of ten buildings under construction that are among the tallest in the world, five are in China.
In my view, this can only be described as madness.
The Chinese economy is being held hostage by real estate investment.
On one hand, China should not rely on maintaining high growth rates in real estate investment to address overcapacity.
Social housing projects are welcome, but currently, real estate investment accounting for as much as 10-13% of GDP is too high.
On the other hand, if real estate investment growth were to fall back, overcapacity would remain unresolved.
This dilemma highlights the structural adjustment challenges China faces – and should also prompt investors to be cautious.
In summary, there are two points worth noting.
Firstly, unlike other types of investment, real estate investment does not increase the stock of productive capital.
There is essentially no difference between houses and high-end durable consumer goods.
Secondly, the growth rate of total fixed asset investment in China is significantly higher than that of total capital formation.
This indicates that the data on the growth rate of fixed investment may overstate the speed of capital stock accumulation.
Therefore, while the Chinese government should resolutely reduce its reliance on investment for economic growth, actions must be extremely cautious.
